	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Tue, May 14th 5:09 PM 2002</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=93579><span id=Sage>Yosa</span></a><br><b><span id=Sage>Sage</span></b><br><span id=notbold>175 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [3.61]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I wonder just what is ment by &quot;maximum damage output&quot;?&nbsp;&nbsp;Sounds like it has something to do with the maximum amount of damage you could do over some time periord.  However the formula doesn't include the weapons delay.  And therefor can not be used to calculate output or any other damage over time number.  <br><br>Yes the Wurmy is better than the Centi Longsword but not by 40%.  <br><br>Yes str does increase the amount of damage you do.  It also helps you to hit more often.  <br><br>If you really want to see the impact of differnt stats (str, agi, etc)  Fight a mob to half life with out a buff and then have a shaman buff that stat, and finish off the mob.  Then fight the next mob to half life with the buff and then remove it. Then calculate your avg damage done or taken or whatever you are intersted in. Do this 10 times or so and you will have a rough idea of what increassing a certain stat does for you.<br><br>However bear in mind that a str or any other stat buff may make very little differance vs a light blue mob, but considerable differance vs a yellow or red mob. <br>Also how much differance imporving a stat make depends a great deal on where you are currently at.  Say you are an oger with low starting agi and you add some +str -agi gear, and drop your agi below 75 and then buff it above 75 you will notice a large differance in how often you get hit and for how much, your ac will also increses signigicantly.  The same buff to a warrior with over 200 agi would have a much smaller impact.   </p>&nbsp;<br> </td></td></tr>
